*Tests represents the total number of tests rather than # of unique people tested. As such, it is important to remember that an individual may have been tested more than once.

2020 Advait Hasabnis

Are We Flattening The Curve?

The doubling time is the time (in days) it will take to double the number of total cases or deaths. Higher doubling time is better! For example, Canada showed a doubling time of 2.75 days at the start of the spread meaning that the total number of cases were doubling approx. every 3 days. We are flattening the curve if the doubling time keeps increasing and the daily new cases continues to drop.

The logarithmic graphs of cumulative cases are used to show the growth rate i.e. the rate at which total cases grow every day. On a logarithmic scale, exponential growth looks like a straight rising line. If a region is slowing the spread, you will see the curve bending down.

This website's analysis is NOT an endorsement to relax or strengthen preventive measures. This is best left to public health experts.
